  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <h1>Best Budget Mechanical Keyboard for Work 2026</h1>
      <div class="meta">Updated June 2026 · Evaluated 7+ models</div>

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#how-we-evaluated">How We Evaluated</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ranking-methodology">Ranking Methodology</a></li>
          <li><a href="#quick-comparison">Quick Comparison</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-overall">Best Overall</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-budget">Best Budget</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-guide">Buying Guide</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <p>If you type for a living, a mechanical keyboard is one of the best investments you can make for your hands. The tactile feedback reduces bottom-out force, the switches last ten times longer than membrane domes, and the right layout can reclaim desk space without losing the keys you actually use. The problem is that most sub-$100 mechanical keyboards force you to choose between Mac compatibility, wireless, and a usable layout. We evaluated seven budget boards based on their specifications and feature sets to find one that does not force those tradeoffs.</p>

      <h2 id="how-we-evaluated">How We Evaluated</h2>
      <p>We evaluated 7 mechanical keyboard models under $100 based on product documentation, specifications, feature analysis, and pricing comparison. Our evaluation methodology follows the <a href="/how-we-test/">ToolStep review protocol</a>, analyzing product documentation, specifications, features, and pricing. Each product was assessed across identical criteria to ensure fair comparison.</p>
      <p>We evaluated each product on four criteria: Performance (30%), Build Quality (25%), Value (20%), and Ease of Use (25%). Scores were compiled from specification analysis and feature evaluation, not marketing claims. For typing performance we assessed switch type, key travel, and actuation force specifications. For wireless reliability we evaluated Bluetooth specifications, multi-device pairing capabilities, and connection stability features. For build quality we assessed case material, keycap material (PBT vs ABS), and construction specifications.</p>

      <h2 id="ranking-methodology">Ranking Methodology</h2>
      <p>Our rankings are based on weighted scoring across four dimensions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Performance (30%)</strong> — Typing feel, switch consistency, and wireless reliability</li>
        <li><strong>Build Quality (25%)</strong> — Case rigidity, keycap quality, and battery longevity</li>
        <li><strong>Value (20%)</strong> — Price-to-performance ratio compared to alternatives</li>
        <li><strong>Ease of Use (25%)</strong> — Layout, Mac/Windows switching, and setup</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="quick-comparison">Quick Comparison</h2>
      <table>
