          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: Keychron K2 (Hot-Swappable)</h2>
      <p>The Keychron K2 won because it was the only keyboard in our comparison that combined a 75% layout, dual Mac and Windows support, wireless, and hot-swappable switches in one package under $80. Most budget boards force you to pick two of those four. The 75% layout is the sweet spot for office work — it keeps the arrow keys and function row that 60% boards sacrifice, but drops the numpad and navigation cluster to reclaim four inches of desk width for your mouse.</p>
      <p>The dual Mac and Windows compatibility is genuinely executed, not just marketing. The keyboard ships with two sets of keycaps (Mac and Windows legends) and a physical OS switch on the side that remaps the modifier keys instantly. According to Keychron's specifications, the keyboard supports pairing with up to three devices and Bluetooth 5.1 maintains a stable connection at up to 6 feet; beyond that, expect occasional stutters, and use the USB-C wired mode for latency-critical work.</p>
      <p>The hot-swappable switches are the feature that future-proofs this keyboard. If you decide the stock Gateron Browns are too tactile or too soft, you can pull the switches with a $5 tool and drop in any compatible MX-style switch — no soldering. According to Keychron's documentation, switch replacement takes under ten minutes. The 4000 mAh battery is among the largest in this category and according to manufacturer specifications delivers up to 72 hours of wireless use with backlighting off. With RGB on at full brightness, expect closer to 12 hours. The case has enough weight (about 2.2 pounds) that it does not slide during energetic typing, and the adjustable feet let you dial in a flat or angled profile.</p>

      <div class="product-box">
